			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: haste<a name="72769"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 31 05 2:53 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Funny, I'm retired for some time now and thought I'd done my last post here some months ago, but somehow this thread ended up being  on my track list and so there was a little EQDiva.com reminder in my mailbox today...
<br />
I got the haste thing wrong in the beginning, but knowing it and having done the research by now there's little to no room for speculation anymore.
<br />
Regular bard haste does not stack with shammie/chanter haste.
<br />
Generally we got three kinds of haste (leaving all the special stuff out):
<br />
Spellhaste (= regular bard/shammie/chanterhaste)
<br />
Itemhaste (= worn haste such as FBSS etc.)
<br />
Overhaste (= bard only stackable spellhaste, referred to as v2 and v3 haste)
<br />

<br />
Spellhaste + Itemhaste can't exceed 100%. So with 40% worn haste it doesn't matter if you get hasted by 60% or 70%, i.e. a shammie, a bard or a chanter.
<br />
Now for overhaste. Both overhastes (v2 and v3) stack with spellhaste. V3 however will get you over the 100% cap, whereas v2 wont. So if you don't reach the cap with item + spell, you can use v2 to get it closer to 100%. If you reach that cap however, v2 is utterly useless. Now if you are at the 100% cap, v3 will get you over that cap to a max of 130% with the best overhaste.
<br />
Oh I just dig haste theory, even when retired.<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
